defaultCIHT is a membership organisation representing over 12,500 people who work in the highways and transportation sector.  CIHT memb
defaulters plan, design, build, operate and maintain best-in-class transport systems and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.
default&#xa0;
defaultCIHT welcomes the opportunity t
defaulto submit evidence to the Committee’s call for evidence. CIHT responses are based on inputs from members of the CIHT who have experience from across the local government H&amp;T sector.
default&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;default     
default 
defaultInvestment in infrastructure to support UK economic 
defaultgrowth is essential and business investor confidence that can be placed in the delivery of that infrastructure 
defaultis 
defaultvital. Uncertainty in this regard 
defaultcould 
defaultplace the UK at a competitive disadvantage in global markets.
default&#xa0;
default     
default 
defaultClarity and certainty on the timi
defaultng of infrastructure investment comes less from change in the decision making process itself, but from having a clear vision of the strategic priorities for the UK.  The identification of those strategic infrastructure priorities has to be driven by an und
defaulterstanding of the key spatial priorities for the UK economy.
default&#xa0;
default   
default 
defaultProgress with the preparation of the National Policy Statement on National Networks is therefore welcomed by the CIHT, providing the potential opportunity to set out a clear long-term framew
defaultork for the development of the country’s transport infrastructure.  However, it is essential that such a policy statement sits within a broader spatial strategy for the country, including, housing, jobs
default, environment
default and infrastructure. One that takes accou
defaultnt of, and builds upon, the economic strengths and potential of key sub-national areas.
default  CIHT will be responding to the government’s consultation in due course.
default&#xa0;
default Such a framework at the national level would provide a clear strategic framework within which
default detailed proposals could be developed by partners at the local level: for the purposes of this submission the argument assumes that the most appropriate ‘local level’ is the functional economic area.
default&#xa0;
default Such considerations become all the more pertinent with the establishment of the Local Growth Fund.  Lord Heseltine’s report ‘No Stone Unturned’ identified the critical importance for the UK to target investment in infrastructure to support economic growth
default and the need to prioritise that investment if the UK economy is to be globally competitive.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ1. default              defaultWhat is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local decision making on transport expenditure?  What are the advantages and disadvantagdefaultes of the Government’s approach?  Are there better models?default&#xa0;
default1.1default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government’s proposals to devolve decision making on expenditure ultimately fits in with their localism agenda – devolving power and responsibility from a national to local level.
default&#xa0;
default1.2default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe over-ri
defaultding consideration for any decision making process is the need to ensure the timely and efficient delivery of the outcomes being sought.
default&#xa0;
default1.3default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe timescales associated with the identification, development and subsequent implementation of major transport scheme
defaults are lengthy: a factor that needs to be taken into account whenever reviewing the need for change to the decision making process for prioritising and allocating funding.
default&#xa0;
default1.4default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWithin the last five years the decision making process for allocating funds to inves
defaultt in transport infrastructure has undergone repeated and fundamental change – from the prioritisation of schemes on a regional/sub national basis, to centralised decision making, to devolution to Local Transport Boards and now to non-statutory partnerships
default led by the Local Enterprise Partnerships working in partnership with local authorities and other partners.
default&#xa0;
default1.5default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultChange to the decision making process is in itself not inherently a bad thing.  However, 
defaultit needs to be remembered that
default any change temporarily adds
default inertia to the delivery process.  The 
defaultChartered Institution of Highways and Transportation (CIHT) is of the view that the 
defaultprofession’s collective ability to improve the efficiency and speed of delivery of infrastructure is inextricably linked to the extent to which there is a degree of 
defaultcontinuity
default and certainty
default in the 
defaultbasis of the 
defaultdecision making process.
default  The creation of the 
defaultSingle Local Growth Fund should assist with certainty of the funding stream.
default&#xa0;
default1.6default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevolution of decision making to the local level has been accompanied by a simplified approach to planning policy.  Whilst the introduction of the National Planning Policy Framew
defaultork has simplified the overarching policy framework, there remains an expectation within the profession, as to the need to retain and reference technical guidance and/or advice.
default&#xa0;
default1.default7default   
defaultThe establishment of Local Enterprise Partnerships
default (LEPs)
default, followed by 
defaultthe opportunity for local partners to work on the development of City-Deal proposals, and now the prospect of Growth Deals, have led to the development of stronger working relationships between public sector organisations, the business community and academ
defaultia.
default  There remains a need to ensure the same level of duty to 
defaultcooperate (
defaultconsider neighbouring authorities
default)
default applies to LEPs and Planning Authorities as the Traffic Management Act places on Local Highway Authorities to address cross boundary concerns
default&#xa0;
default1.8default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSuch initiatives 
defaultcan
default encourage the development of a single narrative for a functional economic area – 
defaultpotentially 
defaultenabl
defaulting
default local partners to better articulate the inter-relationship between investment in transport infrastructure, 
defaultenvironment, 
defaulthousing and skills in support of economic growth across their area.  
defaultWhilst agreeing with the government’s move towards devolution, there is a danger that local response
default 
defaultcould be very local and not joined up, leading to inconsistencies.
default 
default  
default1.9default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal partners 
defaultshould be allowed to build upon this by continuing to be allowed to develop bespoke governance and working arrangements for their area that best reflect their local circumstances.  However, it is accepted that the governance and working arrangements should
default be subject to the approval of Government: to ensure that devolution of funding (with the potential for being held accountable to Parliament) is vested in an appropriately constituted set up.
