defaultQ3default              defaultWhat is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?default&#xa0;
default3.1default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA ‘light touch’ 
defaultnational
default 
defaultspatial strategy, supported by a National Policy Statement on National Ne
defaulttworks, 
defaultwould provide such co-ordinated approach at the national level.  Th
defaulte CIHT argues that this 
defaultwould have two immediate benefits.  Firstly it would reinforce the need for increased cross-Departmental working within Whitehall
default, in the process supporting 
defaultthe establishment of 
defaultthe Local Growth Fund.  Secondly, it would provide local partners with a clear context within which to develop their local proposals
default: proposals that reflect local priorities and which are outcome focused.
default&#xa0;
default3.2default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe issue of transport scheme
defaults that cross local authority boundaries has to be considered in the context of the issues that each scheme might raise.  Where a cross 
defaultboundary scheme is of national significance in its own right, or forms part of a wider corridor approach that is of natio
defaultnal significance, it would seem appropriate for that to be reflected in the national framework.
default&#xa0;
default3.3default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe key consideration for any potential scheme (not just ones that are cross boundary) must be an understanding of the outcome it delivers and how that relates
default to the agreed outcomes for the relevant functional economic area.   By focusing on the delivery of outcomes, schemes that cross local authority boundaries should not be disadvantaged.
