defaultConclusiondefault              
defaultThe approach set out in this submission to 
defaultestablishing the local governance and working arrangements, if 
defaultsupported 
defaultby Government 
defaultthrough the publication of a ‘light-touch’ 
defaultnational spatial strategy would provide clarity 
defaultin terms of 
defaultthe lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe CIHT argues that clarity and stability in the decision making process is essential in order to provide certainty for scheme promoters to invest staff time and 
defaultvaluable revenue funding in the development of proposals.  It is also essential in order to provide confidence to business investors who are looking for a modern and efficient transport system to support economic growth.
default&#xa0;
defaultConstant change to the decision ma
defaultking process in recent years has 
defaultnot given scheme promoters and their delivery partners the confidence to 
defaultmake the 
defaultinvest
defaultment in scheme 
defaultdevelopment that would enable th
defaulte 
defaultrequired 
defaultlong-term investment programme 
defaultfor 
defaultUK 
defaultto come forward
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAs a consequence, w
defaulthen opportunities to secure funding from Government have arisen so the likelihood 
defaultincreases that 
defaultsome of that funding 
defaultis 
defaultallocated to opportunistic schemes simply because they are ready
default.  The existence of an agreed programme of investment determined locall
defaulty within the framework provided by a national spatial strategy would help ensure that the funds available are allocated to the most appropriate schemes.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultCIHT submit that the 
defaultintroduction of the 
defaultSingle 
defaultLocal Growth Fund affords the opportunity to devel
defaultop a truly devolved decision making and funding arrangement.  However, in order to ensure that such an approach is efficient and delivers timely investment it is important that Government provides a ‘light touch’ national spatial strategy: one that is supp
defaultorted by appropriate national policy statements.
